Removing columns

For this session, we will focus on just a small subset of the variables in small_diamonds. The select() function from the dplyr package allows us to select a subset of columns from a larger data frame.

Lets write some code together that creates a new data frame diamonds2 that only contains the variables: carat, cut, depth, price.

# First build the dplyr pipe and make sure you get the right data frame
diamonds2 <- small_diamonds %>%
    select(cut, carat, depth, price)
# Once you know your code is working, do an assignment to the shortcut name diamonds2.  You can do forward assignment -> or backward assignment <-.

Percentiles

Rough guide, my exam grade was better than 72% of my classmates grades, I would say I scored in the 72nd percentile.

  • Notice you do not need to know my actual grade to say this; it is simply a measure of where I stand among the other exam grades

Often we want to reverse this situation: how high do I need to score in order to beat 85% of my classmates? Said differently, What is the 85th percentile score?

Logical vectors and percentiles

A logical vector is simply a vector of TRUE or FALSE values, but R uses them in a number of ways. In general, R will allow you to perform quantitative summaries on logical vectors, and it does this by treating:

  • TRUE is the same as 1
  • FALSE is the same as 0.

This has some fun implications! Yes, I really think this is fun why do you ask?

Run the following code and think about what it does:

# first create a simple vector of numbers:
numbers<- c(1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7)
numbers
## [1] 1 2 3 4 5 6 7
# What does this code do?
numbers < 4
## [1]  TRUE  TRUE  TRUE FALSE FALSE FALSE FALSE

Now lets see how R will treat this logical vector, numbers < 4, if we try to sum() it:

sum(numbers<4)
## [1] 3

Exercise: What percentage of the diamond prices in diamonds2 are above the mean price?

# Here's a guide (not the only way though):

# Compute the mean, save it under mean_price
mean_price <- mean(diamonds2$price)

# Create a logical vector for price values above  mean_price

# diamonds2$price < mean_price

# Use the logical vector to find the total number of diamonds priced above the mean
sum(diamonds2$price < mean_price)
## [1] 251
# take that total number and divide by the total rows in the data frame (nrow() helps)
sum(diamonds2$price < mean_price)/nrow(diamonds2)
## [1] 0.6275

The mean, 3655.418, is actually the 63rd percentile! Is that what we usually expect?

ggplot(data = diamonds2,
       aes(x = price))+
    geom_histogram(color='white',
                   bins = 10)

Alternative approaches:

# the mean of 0's and 1's is a percentage of 1's
mean(diamonds2$price < mean_price)
## [1] 0.6275
# this is kind of ugly actually, but
# we haven't learned some stuff that would make 
# this easier.
mean((diamonds2 %>% pull(price)) < mean_price)
## [1] 0.6275

The harder direction

Suppose we are interested in the following question instead:

  • What is the 80th percentile for the carat measurement?
  • Said differently, how many carats would a diamond need to weight in order to be heavier than 80% of the other diamonds in the data set?

We rely on the quantile() command to find these quickly. To use this properly, you first put your data vector, then pass the percentile you want in next as a decimal. Lets find the 80th percentile of the carat variable:

#Place code here
quantile(diamonds2$carat, 0.8)
##  80% 
## 1.09

Yes, we can use this as part of a summarize() table, so long as we only compute one percentile at a time. Try adding the 80th percentile to the table below.

diamonds2 %>% 
    summarise("mean (carat)" = mean(carat),
              std.dev = sd(carat),
              perc_80 = quantile(carat,.8))
##   mean (carat)   std.dev perc_80
## 1      0.76855 0.4583871    1.09

We can compute a bunch of percentiles at once by passing a vector of probabilities into the probs = argument. For example, try putting c(.1, .25, .5, .75, .9) into that argument:

# Place code here.
quantile(diamonds2$carat, c(.1, .25, .5, .75, .9) )
##  10%  25%  50%  75%  90% 
## 0.31 0.38 0.70 1.01 1.51

Quartiles are a fancy way of referring to the 25th, 50th, and 75th percentiles. Specifically,

  • The first quartile \(Q_1\) is the same as the 25th percentile \(P_{25}\)
  • The second quartile \(Q_2\) is the same as the 50th percentile \(P_{50}\) (also the median)
  • The third quartile \(Q_3\) is the same as the 75th percentile \(P_{75}\)

The summary() command is a great way to get the quartiles, as well as the min, max, and mean of the data set. Try applying summary() to the

#  take your guess!
summary(diamonds$carat)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##  0.2000  0.4000  0.7000  0.7979  1.0400  5.0100

A new measure of variation

We define the inter-quartile range (IQR) to be the difference between the third and first quartiles: Q3 - Q1. The IQR() function computes this quickly in R.

IQR(diamonds2$carat)
## [1] 0.63

(The small difference in IQR based on the IQR() function and the quartiles from summary() come from unimportant decisions on how to compute percentiles.)

The interquartile range is an important measure of variation for certain types of data. Well learn more the in exploration below!

A boxplot is a nice way of visualizing the min, Q1, Q2, Q3 and max of a data set.

  • The lowest dot (or line) is the min,
  • the start of the box is the first quartile
  • the middle line of the box is the median
  • the end of the box is the third quartile
  • the highest dot (or line) is the max.

Here is a box plot for the carat measurement

ggplot(data = diamonds2,
       aes(x = 1, y = carat))+
    geom_boxplot()

Box plots are most useful when you compare them accross different groupings of your data. For example, here is code that would look at carat accross different cuts of diamonds. Notice the x aesthetic is now a grouping variable from the data frame.

ggplot(data = small_diamonds,
       aes(x = cut, y = carat))+
    geom_boxplot()

Here we see that diamonds with a Fair cut have the highest median (middle line of the box), and the least amount of variation as measured by the IQR (the box is shortest!).

Why do we care?

Lets compare two diamond collections. For a private collection, and for the Smithsonian collection, we randomly select 50 diamonds from each.

Run the code below to compare the mean and standard deviation of the carat measurement for each collection.

diamond_compare %>%
    group_by(collection) %>%
    summarise(mean = mean(carat),
              std.dev = sd(carat),
              # add your median and IQR summaries...
              median = median(carat),
              IQR = IQR(carat)
              ) %>%
    # Remember you can only use flip_tibble() inside our lessons.
    flip_tibble()
## # A tibble: 4  3
##   name    Private Smithsonian
##   <chr>     <dbl>       <dbl>
## 1 mean      0.684       1.58 
## 2 std.dev   0.513       6.36 
## 3 median    0.41        0.41 
## 4 IQR       0.585       0.665

Now, add median and IQR (our percentile-based measure of center and spread). What do you notice?

  • The mean and standard deviation imply there is a big difference in the carat measurements between these two collections. However, the median and IQR, do not show the same big difference; they are pretty much the same.

  • Median and IQR are not influenced by outliers, so this could be an indication that there are a few diamonds with either really large carat measurement or really small carat measurements that are influecing the mean and standard deviation to make the collection look different.

Boxplots

Lets try to visualize the difference we are observing above. One common visual that relies on percentile measurements is a boxplot.

To make a boxplot in ggplot, we assign one axis aesthetic to the grouping variable (usually x), and the other to the quantitative variable (usually y). Then, we simply use the geometry geom_boxplot(). Try it below!

# Try to write you code from scratch!
ggplot(data = diamond_compare,
       aes(x = collection,
           y = carat))+
    geom_boxplot()

ggplot(data = diamond_compare,
       aes( x = carat))+
    geom_histogram(bins = 20, color='white') + 
    facet_wrap(vars(collection))

Yikes! Our boxplot got smushed, but at least we are starting to see what the issue might be.
